œÄ(ŒΩ) is a measure for the usefulness of a single node. If œÄ(ŒΩ) = 1 it follows Œπ(ŒΩ) ‚äÜ R and if œÄ(ŒΩ) = 1 it follows
Œπ(ŒΩ) ‚äÜ I. These nodes can be labelled as positive ŒΩ+ or negative ŒΩ‚àí example. In reality, the precision is likely to
be somewhere between these two extremes, which indicates a classiÔ¨Åcation uncertainty ŒΩ? . The recall œÅ(ŒΩ) is less
important for each single node, as other nodes may contain other relevant images.
Node Splitting. Each node which cannot deÔ¨Ånitely be classiÔ¨Åed as positive or negative example should be examined
in more detail. A split criterion can be deÔ¨Åned by a CBIR-query q over the still unclassiÔ¨Åed Œπ(ŒΩ parent ) images. The
query generates a result set r(q) and the remaining data r(q)‚àí1 = (Œπ(ŒΩparent)) \ r(q). These two sets are representing
the content of the two child nodes. The aim is to push the precision of each node either towards 1 or 0 . The ‚Äúleft‚Äù
nodes should move towards 1 and the ‚Äúright‚Äù ones towards 0. The splitting can be recursevely performed until one of
the following situations occurs:
1. The node contains no more images
2. The precision œÄ of the node either reached the upper or lower boundary
3. Generating new splitting queries is not possible
These situations are ‚Äúhard boundaries‚Äù, where further splitting is no more possible or required. For practical use,
these boundaries may be unrealistic and cause an extremely long or even inÔ¨Ånite processing time. Thus, a set of
arbitrary thresholds should be deÔ¨Åned, e.g.:
